What happens when you initialize a repository? why do you need to do it?
A hidden file called .git is created. It's important to do this so that you can create commits in this repository for proper version control and use of git

How is the staging area different from the working directory and the repository? What value do you think it offers?
The staging area is the space between the working directory and the repository, files you want to add to add to a commit get moved to the staging area before being bundled together as a commit to the repository